Greetings from Team 9453,

We are relatively new to robot programming and do not have formal experience in coding. Last year, we successfully utilized code provided by The Everybot. However, this year we are transitioning to a swerve drive system, and the previous code will not be applicable.

Given that we have limited coding knowledge, we are seeking guidance on how to proceed. We have discovered what appears to be suitable code on GitHub, specifically designed for our motors. Here is the link to the code: 2025-OceanGate/src/main/java/frc/robot/RobotContainer.java at main · WARPSPEED4239/2025-OceanGate · GitHub

Could you kindly advise us on the next steps to take?

Thank you for your support.

I take it from the choice of code in that link you have all CTRE motors, CANCoders, and a Pigeon 2? That project is using the CTRE swerve generator. I am still not sure I would use that code as it has things like a USB camera and other things you probably don’t need. If you are looking for something as a “blank slate” comparable to that I would instead start with the official CTRE Swerve with PathPlanner

The next thing you will want to do is make sure whatever code you are starting with (after you have run Swerve Generator and replaced the TunerConstants.java file) work on your robot (it should if using the example above and probably? the example you linked).

After that you will need to code your subsystems, these are things like elevators, arms, intake, climb, etc. This is all dependent on what your robot is doing so we would need to know a lot more to provide advice there.

Even better than fully coding those subsystems is to find another robot doing similar things to yours and use subsystems another team as already written and confirmed are working (you will obviously need to change CAN ids and tune it to your robot but it should be much closer to “complete”).

I would better describe what your robot is doing and what motor controllers are being used and people here can point you in the right direction. If you want to look around on your own I would start with Ri3D robots and Open Alliance teams.

If that is the case that should be easy! (None of this is easy but relatively so)

There is regular kitbot code found here. I took the inline version and attached the Roller Subsystem which is the one you can add to your code in the subsystems folder (that assumes you are using a spark max to drive the roller like the official kitbot). You would then just add some code to RobotContainer to bind buttons to use the subsystem, like:

// Set the A button to run the "runRoller" command from the factory with a fixed
// value ejecting the gamepiece while the button is held
operatorController.a()
    .whileTrue(rollerSubsystem.runRoller(rollerSubsystem, () -> RollerConstants.ROLLER_EJECT_VALUE, () -> 0));

CANRollerSubsystem[1].java (2.2 KB)
